import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_excel("Sample - Superstore.xls")
furniture = df.loc[df['Category'] == 'Furniture']
cols = ['Order Date','Quantity']
furniture = furniture[cols]
furniture = furniture.groupby('Order Date').sum()

We are going to use the tool from statsmodels for timeseries analysis: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/tsa.html

It requires the pandas dataframe to have a datetime index with frequency. Some references here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/60017052/decompose-for-time-series-valueerror-you-must-specify-a-period-or-x-must-be

To change the index, we can use the pandas resample method:

http://pandas-docs.github.io/pandas-docs-travis/user_guide/timeseries.html https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#offset-aliases

Time series decomposition¶

Time series analysis and forecasting is usually viewed as a category of its own, apart from classifications and regressions, although the algorithms are also regression algorithms.

Generally a time series can be decomposed into trend, seasonality and irregular events.

The trend is like a covariate that shifts the mean of the data over time. The seasonality is periodic. The rest is noise.

You can read a book on time series analysis from Hyndman et.al here: https://otexts.com/fpp2/. Because timeseries analysis is a classic one for data scientists, there is a lot more resources in R. This book is also using R, but the concepts are explained very clearly. The decomposition part is here: https://otexts.com/fpp2/decomposition.html; for example, what is the difference between additive and multiplicative decompositions.

statsmodels offer multiple decomposition tools. We compare two of them:

  • Basic seasonal_decompose: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.seasonal_decompose.html#statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.seasonal_decompose
  • STL: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.STL.html#statsmodels.tsa.seasonal.STL

Usually STL is a better method because it considers more flexible seasonality than the basic seasonal decomposition method in statsmodels.

However, STL does not authomatically do multiplicative decomposition. To do so, you have to do a log conversion to the data (our previous class note explains log conversion in data transformation).

In [4]:

Time series forecasting without seasonality¶

The reason for decomposition is to be able to separately forecast the trend and seasonality.

Methods for forecasting without seasonality: moving average (MA) and exponential smoothing (ES): https://people.duke.edu/~rnau/411avg.htm.

Note the error statistics in the post. What do they mean?

Simple moving average SMA¶

Take rolling averages of limited number of data points in the past.

Hyperparameter: number of past data points to consider. The more data points, the smoother the curve, but less responsive to recent changes.

In [8]:

To forecast, we need to define a custom forecast function based on moving average:

In [12]:
def rolling_fcst(historical,window,fcst_length):
    test = historical[-window:]
    for i in range(fcst_length):
        test.append(np.mean(test[-window:]))
    return test[-fcst_length:]

fcst_5 = pd.DataFrame(rolling_fcst(list(trend_train['trend']),
                      window=5,fcst_length=len(trend_test)),
                      index=trend_test.index)
fcst_10 = pd.DataFrame(rolling_fcst(list(trend_train['trend']),
                      window=10,fcst_length=len(trend_test)),
                      index=trend_test.index)
fcst_15 = pd.DataFrame(rolling_fcst(list(trend_train['trend']),
                      window=15,fcst_length=len(trend_test)),
                      index=trend_test.index)

fig,ax = plt.subplots(4,1,figsize=(20,16),sharex=True)
ax[0].plot(trend_train)
ax[0].plot(trend_test)
ax[1].plot(SMA_5,label='5')
ax[1].plot(fcst_5)
ax[1].legend(loc='upper left',prop={'size': 20})
ax[2].plot(SMA_10,label='10')
ax[2].plot(fcst_10)
ax[2].legend(loc='upper left',prop={'size': 20})
ax[3].plot(SMA_15,label='15')
ax[3].plot(fcst_15)
ax[3].legend(loc='upper left',prop={'size': 20})

Brown's simple exponential average SES¶

Considers all data points. weighs the current data point against historical data points. Importance of each historical data is exponentially reduced.

Hyperparameter: exponential weight.

Lower weight means more important history (curve is smoother and less responsive).

In [14]:

Holt's method: double smoothing¶

An exponential smoothing method that separately considers level and trend. By doing so, it explains more of the variance in data, therefore forecast performance is usually better.

Disadvantage: it has two hyperparameters to tune: weight factor for level prediction, and another weight factor for trend prediction.

In [20]:

Methods for forecasting with seasonality¶

Holt's Winters method: tripple smoothing¶

An exponential smoothing method that separately considers level, trend and seasonality. By doing so, it explains even more the variance in data.

Disadvantage: it is a very complex model. Math details is in the book: https://otexts.com/fpp2/holt-winters.html

In [29]:
from statsmodels.tsa.api import ExponentialSmoothing as ES
train_size = int(len(y)/4*3)
y_train = y[0:train_size]
y_test = y[train_size:]

es_custom = ES(y_train,trend='add',seasonal='add',seasonal_periods=52).fit()
fcst_custom = es_custom.forecast(len(y_test))
es_default = ES(y_train).fit()
fcst_default = es_default.forecast(len(y_test))

fig,ax = plt.subplots(3,1,figsize=(20,16),sharex=True)
ax[0].plot(y_train)
ax[0].plot(y_test)
ax[1].plot(es_custom.fittedvalues,label='seasonal periods given')
ax[1].plot(fcst_custom)
ax[1].legend(loc='upper left',prop={'size': 20})
ax[2].plot(es_default.fittedvalues,label='default seasonal periods')
ax[2].plot(fcst_default)
ax[2].legend(loc='upper left',prop={'size': 20})

rmseError_custom = mean_squared_error(y_test, fcst_custom, squared=False)
rmseError_default = mean_squared_error(y_test, fcst_default, squared=False)
print('rmse: custom:{:.2f},default:{:.2f}'.format(rmseError_custom,rmseError_default))

ARIMA method (SARIMA for seasonality)¶

(Seasonal) AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average.

Again, a very good explanation from the book: https://otexts.com/fpp2/arima.html

  • The autoregressive part: https://otexts.com/fpp2/AR.html: the linear regression of current estimate based on past values.

  • The moving average part: https://otexts.com/fpp2/MA.html, this is the moving average of past forecast errors.

  • The integration / differencing part: https://otexts.com/fpp2/stationarity.html

  • the seasonal part: https://otexts.com/fpp2/seasonal-arima.html

To put it together: you have a SARIMA(p,d,q,P,D,Q,Freq) model that has 7 hyperparameters to determine how many variables of each kind you use in the linear regression model, the order of differencing - for both the trend and seasonal parts, as well as the frequency for the seasonal part. An explanation of (p,d,q) is here: https://otexts.com/fpp2/non-seasonal-arima.html. the (P,D,Q) are the same, only for seasonal data.

  • p: order of the autoregressive part
  • d: degree of differencing
  • q: order of the moving average part
  • P: order of autoregressive part bewtween different cycles
  • D: degree of differencing between data points that are one cycle apart
  • Q: order of the moving average part between different cycles
  • Freq: number of data points in each cycle, e.g., 12 for monthly data and yearly cycles; 52 for weekly data and yearly cycles

We use the statsmodels ARIMA method in Python: https://www.statsmodels.org/devel/generated/statsmodels.tsa.arima.model.ARIMA.html

Or directly the seasonal model: https://www.statsmodels.org/devel/generated/statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax.SARIMAX.html using a slightly different method.

Some comparisons of two methods are here: https://www.statsmodels.org/devel/examples/notebooks/generated/statespace_sarimax_faq.html

and here: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/374845/python-arima-generates-different-predictions-than-sarimax-for-same-orders

In [35]:
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
arima = SARIMAX(y_train, trend='ct', order=(1,1,1),
                seasonal_order=(1,1,1,52)).fit()
fcst = arima.forecast(len(y_test))

fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(20,16),sharex=True)
ax[0].plot(y_train)
ax[0].plot(y_test)
ax[1].plot(arima.fittedvalues)
ax[1].plot(fcst)

rmseError = mean_squared_error(y_test, fcst, squared=False)
print('rmse:{:.2f}'.format(rmseError))
